Here‚Äôs a solid starting point for your Rust CLI tool using the `clap`, `serde`, `serde_json`, `walkdir`, and `regex` crates. We'll:

1. Traverse source code files to extract translation keys.
2. Parse translation JSON files (e.g., `en.json`, `fr.json`).
3. Compare them to:
   - Identify unused keys
   - Detect missing keys across translations
4. Emit cleaned translation files and a coverage report.

---

### üöÄ Suggested Project Layout

```
translation-audit/
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ src/
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ main.rs
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ scanner.rs       // Scans codebase for used keys
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ parser.rs        // Parses and compares translation files
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ report.rs        // Generates summary and cleaned files
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ translations/
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ en.json
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ fr.json
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Cargo.toml
```

---

### üì¶ Dependencies (in `Cargo.toml`)

```toml
[dependencies]
clap = { version = "4.0", features = ["derive"] }
walkdir = "2.4"
regex = "1"
serde = { version = "1", features = ["derive"] }
serde_json = "1"
```

---

### üß† Code Sketch: `main.rs`

```rust
mod scanner;
mod parser;
mod report;

use clap::Parser;

#[derive(Parser)]
struct Cli {
    #[arg(short, long, default_value = "src")]
    source: String,
    #[arg(short, long, default_value = "translations")]
    translations: String,
}

fn main() {
    let cli = Cli::parse();

    let used_keys = scanner::extract_used_keys(&cli.source);
    let parsed = parser::load_translation_files(&cli.translations);

    let results = parser::compare_keys(&used_keys, &parsed);
    report::generate(&results, &cli.translations);
}
```

---

### üß© Scanner Example (`scanner.rs`)

```rust
use regex::Regex;
use std::fs;
use walkdir::WalkDir;
use std::collections::HashSet;

pub fn extract_used_keys(dir: &str) -> HashSet<String> {
    let re = Regex::new(r#"t!\(\s*"([^"]+)""#).unwrap();
    let mut keys = HashSet::new();

    for entry in WalkDir::new(dir)
        .into_iter()
        .filter_map(Result::ok)
        .filter(|e| e.path().is_file())
    {
        if let Ok(content) = fs::read_to_string(entry.path()) {
            for cap in re.captures_iter(&content) {
                keys.insert(cap[1].to_string());
            }
        }
    }

    keys
}
```

